wild apes.In Smitten by Giraffe the noted feminist reflects on her scientific work as well as the leading role she has played in numerous activist campaigns. On returning home to Canada, Anne married physicist Ian Dagg, had three children, published a number of scientific papers, taught at several local universities, and in 1967 earned her PhD in biology at the University of Waterloo. Dagg was continually frustrated in her efforts to secure a position as a tenured professor despite her many publications and exemplary teaching record. Finally she opted instead to pursue her research as an independent “citizen scientist,” while working part-time as an academic advisor. Dagg would spend many years fighting against the marginalization of women in the arts and sciences.Boldly documenting widespread sexism in universities while also discussing Dagg’s involvement with important zoological topics such as homosexuality, infanticide, sociobiology, and taxonomy, Smitten by Giraffe offers an inside perspective on the workings of scientific research and debate, the history of academia, and the rise of second-wave feminism. A new preface relates Dagg’s experience as the subject of the documentary The Woman Who Loves Giraffes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGiraffezAfrica. 0aSexism in higher education - Canada. 0aSexism in higher educationzCanada. 0aWomen college teacherszCanadavBiography. 0aWomen in higher educationzCanada. 0aWomen scientistszCanadavBiography. 0aWomen zoologistszCanadavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Science & Technology.2bisacsh  aSTEM.  aacademia.  aautobiography.  aenvironment.  afeminism.  agiraffes.  aresearch.  ascience.  asexism.  asociobiology.  ataxonomy.  auniversities.  awomen.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359974140uhttps://www.degruyter.co